    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.801/621</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<hi
                        rend="italic">Phillips</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-18">June 18,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I asked the President whether, in fact, he was planning a conference to consider
                    ship subsidy legislation. He said he was not planning any such conference and
                    seemed not to be interested in it. I said that, if he had been going to discuss
                    it, I wanted to bring to his attention the Secretary’s letter to Senator
                        Copeland,<note n="18" xml:id="d363fn18">See footnote 13, <ref
                            target="#pg_477">p. 477</ref>.</note> which was a very important
                    statement and which he would naturally wish to see. The President, however, did
                    not seem to wish to go into the matter and I did not, therefore, leave this
                    letter with him.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
